 8 + 5 + 0 - 2 = 11\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: values = [1,2]\nOutput: 2\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n2 <= values.length <= 5 * 104\n1 <= values[i] <= 1000\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maxScoreSightseeingPair(self, values: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maxScoreSightseeingPair(self, values: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Initialize the maximum score with the first possible pair\n        max_score = values[0] + values[1] + 0 - 1\n        # Initialize the best value of values[i] + i seen so far\n        best_i = values[0] + 0\n        \n        # Iterate over the array starting from the second element\n        for j in range(1, len(values)):\n            # Calculate the score for the current pair (best_i, j)\n            current_score = best_i + values[j] - j\n            # Update the maximum score if the current score is higher\n            max_score = max(max_score, current_score)\n            # Update the best value of values[i] + i seen so far\n            best_i = max(best_i, values[j] + j)\n        \n        return max_score\n```\n\nThis solution efficiently computes the maximum score of a pair of sightseeing spots by keeping track of the best value of `values[i] + i` seen so far, allowing us to calculate the score for each `j` in constant time. This results in an overall time complexity of O(n), where n is the length of the input list `values`.", "estimated_date": 1553385600000}